ladders.explanation:
This is the reconstruction step after addition. The intuition is that to get digits in reverse order, we extract the least significant digit first using modulo 10, then remove that digit by integer division. For example, for integer 807: 807%10=7 (ones digit), create node 7; 807//10=80; 80%10=0 (tens digit), create node 0; 80//10=8; 8%10=8 (hundreds digit), create node 8; 8//10=0 stop. The algorithm: 1) If num=0, return a single node with value 0. 2) Initialize a dummy head node to simplify linking. 3) While num>0: a) digit = num % 10. b) Create new node with value digit. c) Link it to current list. d) num = num // 10. 4) Return dummy.next. Time complexity is O(d) where d is number of digits in num, which is O(max(n,m)) from original lists. Space complexity is O(d) for the new list. Connection to L0: This builds the final result in L0. Common mistakes: not handling num=0 case, building list in wrong order (should append new nodes to end), and forgetting to update num after extracting digit. Real code pattern: def int_to_reversed_list(num):
    if num == 0:
        return ListNode(0)
    dummy = ListNode(0)
    curr = dummy
    while num > 0:
        curr.next = ListNode(num % 10)
        curr = curr.next
        num //= 10
    return dummy.next
